stylometry: Bayesian analysis uses management experience, research, and relevant data to determine probabilities used in decision theory. It is important because it allows us to readjust our data to make it more helpful and realistic. We begin with a prior probability, which is the chance an outcome will occur before it happens. Then when we get results after the event, we can combine them with the prior probability to create a posterior probability. We need these new posterior probabilities to help make more effective management decisions through revised and updated information. An example of this would be that the probability that a question asking what the elasticity of demand is would be on this test was 50% before we took the test. Next, perhaps after we took the test and the question was not on the test for one section of the class, but not for the other 2 sections (33%). The posterior probability would be the combination of the 50% prior probability and the new 33%.
